(a) These HELOCs are predominantly revolving loans for a 10-year period, after which time the HELOC converts to a loan with a 20-year amortization period, but
also include HELOCs that allow interest-only payments beyond the revolving period.
(b) The Firm manages the risk of HELOCs during their revolving period by closing or reducing the undrawn line to the extent permitted by law when borrowers are
experiencing financial difficulty.
HELOCs beyond the revolving period and HELOANs have higher delinquency rates than HELOCs within the revolving period.
That is primarily because the fully-amortizing payment that is generally required for those products is higher than the minimum
payment options available for HELOCs within the revolving period. The higher delinquency rates associated with amortizing
HELOCs and HELOANs are factored into the Firm’s allowance for loan losses.
